2","1060":"1060","Burgh Next Aylsham, Norfolk, England":"Burgh next Aylsham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England"},"nl":{"1058–":"1058–Overleden","1060–1085":"1060–1085","1082–1112":"1082–1112","1058–Male":"1058–Overleden","1106":"1106","um 1081":"circa 1081","1058":"1058","1112":"1112","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1085":"1085","1082":"1082","1060":"1060","Burgh Next Aylsham, Norfolk, England":"Burgh next Aylsham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1058–":"1058–Deceased","1060–1085":"1060–1085","1082–1112":"1082–1112","1058–Male":"1058–Deceased","1106":"1106","um 1081":"about 1081","1058":"1058","1112":"1112","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1085":"1085","1082":"1082","1060":"1060","Burgh Next Aylsham, Norfolk, England":"Burgh next Aylsham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":8,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705183,"age":28,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":38,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705185,"age":48,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Daisnel I was born in 1058, in Norfolk, England. He married Emma Agnes Capet about 1081, in Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1058–":"1058–Surnud","1060–1085":"1060–1085","1082–1112":"1082–1112","1058–Male":"1058–Surnud","1106":"1106","um 1081":"umbes 1081","1058":"1058","1112":"1112","1066":"1066","1086":"